\section{[[prof]] and [[tprof]] command-line interfaces}
%\section{[[kprof]] command-line interface}

%claude:
[[prof]] reads a profile data file ([[prof.<pid>]])
produced by an instrumented program and correlates it with
the program's symbol table. For each function, it prints
the percentage of time spent there, the absolute time, and
the call count. The [[-d]] flag prints the dynamic call
graph instead, showing the tree of calls indented by depth.

%claude:
[[tprof]] works differently: it reads
[[/proc/<pid>/profile]], which contains
interrupt-time samples of the program counter collected
by the kernel. Since sampling cannot track calls,
[[tprof]] has no [[-d]] (call graph) option---it only
reports time per function.

To enable sampling, you first write ``[[profile]]'' to
[[/proc/<pid>/ctl]], let the program run, then
run [[tprof <pid>]] while the process is still alive.

%claude:
[[kprof]] is a variant of [[prof]] that profiles the
kernel itself. It reads the data accumulated by the
[[kprof(3)]] device ([[/dev/kpdata]]), which records
one count per clock tick per 8-byte range of kernel text.

\section{[[trace]] and [[stats]] graphical user interfaces}

%claude:
[[trace]] and [[stats]] are graphical programs that display
system activity in real time.
[[trace]] reads events from [[/proc/trace]] and draws a
timeline for each traced process: colored blocks show
when a process is running, and arrows mark scheduling
events (releases, deadlines, yields, overruns).
The user can zoom in and out with [[+]]/[[-]] and pause
with [[p]].

%claude:
[[stats]] reads counters from kernel pseudo-files
([[#c/sysstat]], [[#c/swap]], [[/net/ether0/0/stats]])
and plots rolling graphs updated once per second.
It can display dozens of metrics: system load, memory
usage, context switches, syscalls, interrupts, TLB
misses, network packets, and more. It can even monitor
multiple machines simultaneously, drawing their graphs
in adjacent columns.
[[stats]] is similar in spirit to tools like GNOME System
Monitor on Linux or Activity Monitor on macOS, but it
runs in a terminal-sized window and focuses on kernel-level
counters rather than per-process resource usage.

%yoann: maybe explain a few of the flags from usage string?
%claude:
The lower-case flags select which metrics to display.
The most commonly used are
[[-l]] for system load (the default),
[[-m]] for memory usage,
[[-c]] for context switches per second,
[[-s]] for syscalls per second,
[[-i]] for interrupts per second, and
[[-e]] for network packets.
Upper-case flags control the display:
[[-S]] sets a scale factor,
[[-L]] switches to logarithmic axes, and
[[-Y]] adds value markers along the y axis.

<<function usage (misc/stats.c)>>=
void
usage(void)
{
    fprint(2, "usage: stats [-O] [-S scale] [-LY] [-%s] [machine...]\n", argchars);
    exits("usage");
}
@


\section{[[iostats]] filesystem interface}

%claude:
[[iostats]] takes yet another approach: it is a
user-level {file server} that interposes itself between a
program and the regular file server, intercepting all 9P
messages. When the program exits, [[iostats]] prints a
report showing how much data was read and written, the
number and latency of each 9P message type, and a
per-file I/O summary.
This is a classic \plan design: instead of adding
tracing hooks inside the kernel, you insert a proxy file
server in the namespace.
%
For example, [[iostats ls]] runs [[ls]] through the
proxy and reports how many [[read]], [[stat]], and
[[open]] messages that simple command generates.

\section{Profiling [[hello]]}


% time
% prof
% tprof
% trace
% stats
% iostats

%claude:
To get a feel for the tools, consider profiling the simplest
possible program, [[hello]]. 


%yoann: maybe show simple example of hello.c calling bar and foo in different loops so can also see callgraph
%claude:
For a more interesting example, consider a program that
calls [[foo]] in a loop and [[bar]] once, where [[foo]]
itself calls [[bar]]:
\begin{verbatim}
  void bar(void) { /* some work */ }
  void foo(void) { bar(); /* more work */ }
  void main(void) {
      int i;
      for(i = 0; i < 100; i++)
          foo();
      bar();
      exits(nil);
  }
\end{verbatim}

With [[time]]:
\begin{verbatim}
  % time hello
  hello world
  0.00u 0.00s 0.01r    hello
\end{verbatim}
The three numbers are user time, system time, and real
(wall-clock) time, all in seconds.

%claude:
With [[prof]], you first link with [[-p]] to enable
instrumentation, run the program, then display the results:
\begin{verbatim}
  % 5l -p -o hello hello.5
  % hello
  % prof hello
    %     Time    Calls  Name
   60.0    0.06      100  foo
   30.0    0.03      101  bar
   10.0    0.01        1  main
\end{verbatim}

%yoann: maybe also show session with prof -d for call graph?
%claude:
The [[-d]] flag shows the dynamic call graph instead:
\begin{verbatim}
  % prof -d hello
  main:10/1
    foo:60/100
      bar:20/100
    bar:10/1
\end{verbatim}
This reveals that [[bar]] was called from two sites:
100 times from [[foo]] and once directly from [[main]].

%claude:
With [[tprof]], you start a longer-running program, enable
profiling, and then read the sampling data:
\begin{verbatim}
  % longrun &
  % echo profile > /proc/$apid/ctl
  % # ... let it run ...
  % tprof $apid
    %     Time  Name
   45.0    4.50  compute
   30.0    3.00  process
   15.0    1.50  sort
   10.0    1.00  main
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
With [[iostats]], you see the 9P traffic:
\begin{verbatim}
  % iostats hello
  hello world
  read     32 bytes, 1 ops     ...
  write    12 bytes, 1 ops     ...
  protocol 48 bytes
  rpc       4
\end{verbatim}

